	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: &quot;Always&quot; is a strong word.</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">"Always" is a strong word. <em>Super Mario Galaxy</em> for Wii uses cutscenes to cover up loading, and you can't make a "NOW LOADING" screen skippable now, can you?</div><br /><br />Fair enough.  I guess if it's covering a loading screen then that's a legitimate reason for it to be not skippable.<br /><br />Although if the loading finishes before the cutscene is over, or if the loading would be faster without the cutscene, it should definitely be skippable.<br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And how will you convince the lawyers to let the player skip the screen with copyright and trademark notices on it?</div><br /><br />Put it in the manual, or on the title screen.<br /><br />Everyone knows things are copyrighted and trademarked.<br /><br />Having it mentioned somewhere discreet in the game will suffice for all legal purposes.  As long as it's <em>there</em>, it counts (and with copyrights I think it might count even if it isn't there).<br /><br />That kind of thing can (and should) be left to the fine print.  I shouldn't have to wait 2 minutes to view a copyright notice I've seen a million times.  That's just stupid.  It's bad enough I have to put up with that crap at the beginning of movies.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And how will you handle players who are angry that they don't know where to go because they skipped the cut scene telling them the mission objective?</div>
<br />
<br />Any of the following:
<br />
<br />1)  Don't make the mission objective so obscure that it can't be figured out with casual gameplay.
<br />2)  Have an option in the menu that says "view mission objective".
<br />3)  Have a mark on the map indicating where you go next
<br />
<br />These are all pretty typical in the games I play.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


