	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Disch</b> [ Sat Jun 05, 2010 12:27 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">UncleSporky wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Personally I have no remorse for players who don't bother to sit through potentially vital information.</div><br /><br />Then you'd be a poor game designer.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If you can't be bothered to watch for objectives then maybe you should be playing a different game.</div><br /><br />Games <em>shouldn't be</em> a bother.  That's the opposite of what a game is.<br /><br />You're forgetting the point of a game is supposed to be that it's entertaining and fun.<br /><br />Watching cutscenes is not fun for a lot of people.  Especially if they've already played through the game a few times.<br /><br />If watching [what you find to be boring] cutscenes, and actually paying attention to them in case there's some "vital" information is a requirement of the game, then by extention that makes the game boring and not fun.  Which in turn makes it a bad game.<br /><br />So yeah.  If your game is no fun, then you're right.  They should be playing a different game.  And they probably will.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Cutscenes should be skippable but that doesn't mean they need to also be irrelevant to playing the game itself.  The player pays the price for not paying attention, whether it's a monster attacking him from behind or a scene telling him what he needs to know.</div><br /><br />If the cutscene is 2 seconds and says "do this" that's one thing.<br /><br />If the cutscene is 5 minutes of crap you don't care about with 2 seconds of important info buried in the middle of it, that sucks.<br /><br />Games are games.  They're not jobs.  Players shouldn't have to work or suffer to play them.  They're supposed to just play them and enjoy it.  It's the programmers and game designer's job to do the actual work to make it easy/fun for the player.  That's why they make the money.<br /><br /><br /><br />EDIT:<br /><br />Let me put it this way:  it's a business model.<br /><br />When I go to a restaurant, I pay the restaurant to cook me food, bring it to me, and give me whatever related service I ask for, whether it be a certain condiment, some dessert, or a refill of my drink.  They do it for me.  That's why I pay them money.<br /><br />When I go to a store, I pick out the item I want.  If I can't find it, I ask the customer service guy if he can find it for me.<br /><br />It's the old addage "the customer is always right".<br /><br />If I ask my server at a restaurant to bring me a refill of my drink and they say "do it yourself, I'm busy", that a crappy restaurant.<br /><br />If I ask a customer service guy to help me find a product and he says "that's not my job", that's a crappy store.<br /><br /><br />The business does not expect the customer to do the work.  The business does the work.  That's why it's the business.  The customer is giving money to the business so that they don't have to work.  That's the whole point.<br /><br /><br />To relate that to this gaming discussion:<br /><br />The player is the customer.  He's buying the game because he wants to be entertained.<br /><br />The game designer is the business.  He's getting paid to make an entertaining game.<br /><br />If the player asks "what am I supposed to be doing in this game now?" and the game says "tough shit, you should've watched that 5 minute cutscene at the start of the level", then that's a crappy game.<br /><br />Now I'm not saying that every game should be fun for every player.  That's obviously not realistic.  What I'm saying is that the game should cater to the player as much as possible.<br /><br />In your post:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I have no remorse for players who don't bother to sit through potentially vital information.</div>
<br />
<br />You clearly are not catering to the player.  In fact you're adamantly opposing extending service to the player.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


