		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">UncleSporky wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Personally I have no remorse for players who don't bother to sit through potentially vital information.</div><br /><br />Then you'd be a poor game designer.</div><br />Nope.  Poor is a relative term.<br /><br />I have the same lack of remorse for players who don't read the manual and get upset when they don't know how to jump, or who skip the "boring tutorial" and get upset when they don't know how to equip an item...or those who don't watch a scene that gives them vital information.<br /><br />In short, the player has responsibility to absorb the information I give him if he wants to enjoy my game.  I'm not a bad designer if he refuses my help.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Watching cutscenes is not fun for a lot of people.  Especially if they've already played through the game a few times.</div><br /><br />And watching scenes is the primary reason some people play video games.  Everyone has their own tastes, and it's up to the consumer to buy games that match theirs.<br /><br />If you only like football games you shouldn't buy an RPG.  If you don't like twitch games with precise movement you shouldn't buy a shooter.  And if you don't like watching cutscenes then you shouldn't buy a cinematic, story-heavy game.<br /><br />No game developer attempts to make a game that absolutely everyone will enjoy, because the game often ends up a mess that nobody likes, mediocre in all aspects.  A good developer knows their specific target audience and makes a game tailored to them.  Nippon Ichi doesn't try to put twitch platforming in their strategy RPGs because they know their target audience doesn't want that.  Konami makes long, drawn out, highly complicated cutscenes in Metal Gear because they know their target audience wants that.  Either way, it's primarily your own fault for not researching the type of game if you buy it and end up not liking it.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">So yeah.  If your game is no fun, then you're right.  They should be playing a different game.  And they probably will.</div><br />"No fun" being a relative term, I would hope so!  I don't want someone writing me a nasty letter saying "yo dawg I just wanted to play some Madden but your RPG doesn't have any playbooks and I can't tackle, therefore your game sucks."<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If the cutscene is 2 seconds and says "do this" that's one thing.<br /><br />If the cutscene is 5 minutes of crap you don't care about with 2 seconds of important info buried in the middle of it, that sucks.</div><br />Hey, relative again.  Don't play the games if you think they suck, meanwhile the throng of players who do care to watch the scenes and learn secrets from them will be over here enjoying it.<br /><br />It's the same complaint from the people who don't talk to every NPC in an RPG and get lost - they think they should be able to complete the game without talking to anyone.  This is the wrong genre for that person.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If the player asks "what am I supposed to be doing in this game now?" and the game says "tough shit, you should've watched that 5 minute cutscene at the start of the level", then that's a crappy game.</div>
<br />Again: nope.
<br />
<br />You used the example of restaurants.  Here's another way to put what you're saying to me:
<br />
<br />If the customer asks "can I buy prime rib here?" and the restaurant says "tough shit, this is a Taco Bell," then that's a crappy restaurant.
<br />
<br />What I'm saying is the customer needs to pay more attention at what's being offered when they first pull into the drive through.

		

